Business dynamics among California, Texas and the U.S.

Meng Zhang

11/13/2021

1.Introduction

The U.S. economy is comprised of more than 6 million establishments with paid employees. The population of these businesses is constantly churning - some businesses grow, others decline, and yet others close. New businesses constantly replenish this pool. Modern market economies are characterized by the reallocation of resources from different businesses and  businesses play a particularly important role in this reallocation by introducing new products and services that impact the entire economy. Hence, tracking the performance of each sector of business is therefore of primary importance.  

Texas stands head and shoulders above all other states in the race to attract corporate headquarters exiting California, with Dallas-Fort Worth and Austin topping the list of destinations within the Lone Star State. In 2021, California lost 53 headquarters to other states between Jan. 1 and June 27, and 23 of those companies went to Texas drawn by low taxes, cheap houses and a low-regulation lifestyle.  

In this paper, we will compare Business Dynamics Statistics (BDS) among California, Texas and the United States to track changes in different business sector at the firm level, and thus provide a virtualization of the dynamics underlying aggregate net business growth. Government may make better decisions on regulation and deregulation, and individuals may find their direction of education, career and home settlement through the result.

2.Data

The data was firm-level which extract from the Business Dynamics Statistics (BDS) , the original BDS data was export from  the website of the United States Census Bureau. Establishments are used in tabulating the BDS statistics. An establishment is a fixed physical location where economic activity occurs. A firm may have one establishment (a single-unit establishment) or many establishments (a multi-unit firm). Firms are defined at the enterprise level such that all establishments under the operational control of the enterprise are considered part of the firm. Firm-level data are compiled based on an aggregation of establishments under common ownership by a corporate parent using Census Bureau company identification numbers. This paper retrieved annual firm statistics of the total of all sectors and 18 business sectors among California, Texas and the United States from 2010 to 2018. The 18 business sectors are :

A.Mining,quarring and oil and gas extraction;

B.Utilities;

C.Construction;

D.Manufacturing;

E.Wholesale trade;

F.Retail trade;

G.Transportation and warehousing;

H.Information;

I.Finance and insurance;

J.Real estate and rental and leasing;

K.Professional, scientific, and technical services;

L.Management of companies and enterprises;

M.Administrative and support and waste management and remediation services;

N.Educational services;

O.Health care and social assistance;

P.Arts, entertainment, and recreation;

Q.Accommodation and food services;

R.Other services (except public administration).

The data was in excel format, scaled and calculated in growth amount and growth rate for each sector among different region.

3.Data Visualization

The purpose of this project is to translate information into a visual context, make data easier to understand, let us quickly identify patterns, trends and outliers in large data sets. People would more intuitively see the business dynamics in various sectors among California, Texas and compare their changing with that of the Unite States from 2010 to 2018.  

In this project, the bar chart was built with R language ggplot2. The bar chart is used to show each data category in a frequency distribution, summarize a large data set in visual form, estimate key values at a glance, and permit a visual check of the accuracy and reasonableness of calculations.   

We choose a horizontal bar chart because it can display the sector names in a straightforward manner just by making the chart taller, and each sector is the name of a pair of variables and the bar chart shows the correlation between the two variables. Labels for many bars are easier to display without collision. The code we set the bar chart horizontal was “coord_flip()”.    

The data of California, the Texas, and the United States were grouped separately,  with x-axis represents the growth rate as business dynamics and y-axis represents each sector of industry in different region. We can clearly compare growth rate with each sector of different regions, to analyze which sector has higher or lower growth rate with correspondents. The figure 5 shows the R Code of bar chart.

Load Packages

            position = position_dodge(0.9),size = 2.2) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = 'Accent') +
  theme_classic() +
  coord_flip()

4.Shiny App

To make the bar chart more interactive, easier to analyse and communicate with the result, we build a Shiny app straight from R and publish it to the shinyapp.io. In this progress, R-Studio takes care of all of the details of hosting the app and maintaining the server, Shinyapps.io provides online service for hosting Shiny app in the cloud.
library(readr)
library(shiny)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(ggplot2)
require("readr")
require("shiny")
library(tidyverse)
# gr <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MengZhang2021/DataVisualization/master/Growthrate.csv")
gr <- read_csv("Growthrate.csv")
ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel(title = h4("Business dynamics among California, Texas and the U.S. 2010-2018", align="center")),
  sidebarPanel(
    textInput(inputId = "caption",
              label = "Caption:",
              value = "Sectors"),
    selectInput("Sector", "Select the Sector",
                 choices = c("Average Growth Rate",
                             "Mining,quarring and oil and gas extraction",
                             "Utilities",
                             "Construction",
                             "Manufacturing",
                             "Wholesale trade",
                             "Retail trade",
                             "Transportation and warehousing",
                             "Information",
                             "Finance and insurance",
                             "Real estate and rental and leasing",
                             "Professional, scientific, and technical services",
                             "Management of companies and enterprises",
                             "Administrative and support and waste management and remediation services",
                             "Educational services",
                             "Health care and social assistance",
                             "Arts, entertainment, and recreation",
                             "Accommodation and food services",
                             "Other services (except public administration)"),
                 selected = "Average Growth Rate")),
  mainPanel(
    plotOutput("bar",height=500))
)

server <- function(input,output){
  reactive_data = reactive({
    selected_Sector = input$Sector
    return(gr[gr$Sectors==selected_Sector,])
    
  })
  
  output$caption <- renderText({
    input$caption
  })
  output$bar <- renderPlot({
    color <- c(rgb(0.3,0.1,0.4,0.6) , rgb(0.2,0.4,0.6,0.6) , rgb(0.8,0.1,0.1,0.6))
    our_data <- reactive_data()
    bp <- barplot(colSums(our_data[,c("US","California","Texas")]),
                  ylab="Growth Rate",
                  ylim =c(-20,50),
                  xlab="Region",
                  names.arg = c("US","California","Texas"),
                  col = color)
    text(bp,5,labels=our_data[c("US","California","Texas")])
    text(3,100,labels = "Unit=Percent")
    legend("topright", legend = c("US","California","Texas"),
           col = c(rgb(0.3,0.1,0.4,0.6) , rgb(0.2,0.4,0.6,0.6) , rgb(0.8,0.1,0.1,0.6)) , 
           bty = "n", pch=20 , pt.cex = 2, cex = 1.5, horiz = FALSE, inset = c(0.05, 0.05))
  })
}
shinyApp(ui=ui, server=server)

5.Conclusion

From the project, we can see in the total of all sectors among California , Texas and the United States, the growth rate of the United states is 5.29%, the growth rate of California is 10.94%, the growth rate of Texas is 12.58%, both growth rate of California and Texas are bigger than that of the United States and Texas stands head above them.  

In the sectors of constructions, transportation and warehousing, professional ,scientific and technical services, management of companies and enterprises, administrative and support and waste management and remediation services, educational services, health care and social assistance, accommodation and food services, the growth rate of Texas are apparently higher than that of California and the United states. Even in some sectors with negative growth, Texas still show better performance than the others, for example, in the sector of mining, quarrying and oil and gas extraction, the growth rates of California and the United States are -16.34% and -6.55% but that of Texas is 0.07%, in the sector of manufacturing, the growth rates of California and the United States are -3.96% and -4.72%, but that of Texas is -0.42%. One of the reason is more and more companies in California went to Texas over period.  

California is an attractive business location due to a highly skilled labor force, a well-developed infrastructure and access to a wide variety of capital resources. The state has consistently polled first in terms of favorite states in which to live. However, it is relatively expensive when compared with many parts of the United States. In particular, real estate prices are high .Worker's compensation premiums were the highest in the country. Energy costs are higher than the national average, with electricity rates the highest of any state. Corporate taxation and regulation are considered unfavorable etc.  

Many factors encouraging companies to abandon the nice weather on the coast. The companies that move to Texas span every sector. But their reasoning is mostly the same: the pro-business climate with no corporate or personal income tax, the central location, the large Dallas-Fort Worth(DFW) International Airport, the state's accessible talent pool, and the quality of life it offers and the support including incentives from cities.  

When companies think of moving or growing, they're thinking, “Will this place we're moving to be great five, twenty  and thirty years from now?” Both California and Texas present opportunities for different sectors, their large consumer market provides numerous opportunities for a business to not only establish itself, but to grow and thrive.What they should to is to invest in their future by offering competitive incentives to companies that create jobs and drive innovation.  

Future research can construct extensions to the business dynamics statistics focus on specific sectors. For example, businesses in the High Technology sector play a particularly important role in the relocation by introducing new products and services that impact the entire economy. Tracking the performance of this sector is therefore of primary importance, especially in light of recent evidence that suggests a slowdown in business dynamism in High Tech industries.
